                    <heading>Judicial System</heading>
                    <p id="BG.DIR.224">The judicial system is independent, most appointments being made or recommended by the Supreme Judicial Council (SJC), a permanent, supervisory body. Administrative courts review appeals of government acts. The SJC comprises 25 members, and following reforms in 2015 is divided into two units, one responsible for judges' affairs and one for prosecutorsâ€™. The Chairmen of the two Supreme Courts and the Prosecutor-General are senior ex officio members. The Constitutional Court is the final arbiter of constitutional issues. It comprises 12 judges, who serve nine-year terms, four of whom are appointed by the President, four by the National Assembly and four by the Supreme Courts. A special court opened in Sofia in January 2012, to expedite organized crime trials.</p>
